#MEM id=Daniel_Kahneman source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Psychology/Daniel_Kahneman/principles.md
M|Daniel_Kahneman|1. **Representativeness** — Judge probability by similarity to stereotype, ignoring base rates
M|Daniel_Kahneman|2. **Availability** — Judge likelihood by ease of recall, ignoring statistical evidence
M|Daniel_Kahneman|3. **Anchoring** — Rely heavily on first piece of information received
M|Daniel_Kahneman|4. **Framing Effect** — Same outcome, different presentation = different choice
M|Daniel_Kahneman|5. **Loss Aversion** — Losses hurt 2x more than gains feel good
M|Daniel_Kahneman|6. **Status Quo Bias** — Preference for current state without analysis
M|Daniel_Kahneman|| System | Speed | Source | Error Type |
M|Daniel_Kahneman||--------|-------|--------|------------|
M|Daniel_Kahneman|| **System 1** | Fast | Intuition | Overconfidence |
M|Daniel_Kahneman|| **System 2** | Slow | anl | Calculation cost |
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Every intuitive judgment gets analytic verification
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Confidence intervals must reflect base rate probability
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Re-calibrate after feedback loops
M|Daniel_Kahneman|1. **Independence** — Events don't affect each other, but humans don't calculate
M|Daniel_Kahneman|2. **Neglect** — Most probability reasoning is qualitative, not quantitative
M|Daniel_Kahneman|3. **Correction** — Replace intuition with explicit math
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Make invisible costs visible
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Make hidden assumptions explicit
M|Daniel_Kahneman|- Always ask: "What does System 2 say?"